{"cells":[{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"# Lab: Configure Fields and Create Calculated Fields","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Overview","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"This lab covers field configuration on Types and creating calculated fields, which use dot notation to compute field values from other fields on Types.\n\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\">\n    Each learning objective corresponds with a <b>#TODO</b> in the notebook activities.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### Estimated time","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"This lab will take approximately **1 hour** to complete.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### Learning objectives","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After completing this lab, you will be able to:\n- Make fields required.\n- Create enumerated fields on a Type.\n- Recognize calculated field syntax. \n- Define calculated fields using expression engine functions and dot notation.\n- Refresh the computed data on a stored calc field.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Lab support","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"For guidance on the activities, please refer to the <a href=\"../src/doc/academyFundamentals-overview.c3doc.md\">solutions</a>. You can also refer to the [troubleshooting tips and tricks](../labs/troubleshooting.md) if you run into issues.\n\nFor additional support, check out the <a href=\"https://learn.c3.ai/page/help-center\" target=\"_blank\">Help Center</a> for office hours information.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Setup","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 1. Prerequisites","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Lab 2, `connect-and-traverse-data-model.c3nb`, is a prerequisite for completing the activities in this lab. ","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 2. Application selection","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"When you complete this C3 notebook, you want to run the commands against the right application. Before you continue with the lab, open the dropdown menu by selecting **Select Application** in the toolbar. This displays a list of applications in your environment. Choose the application with `root package: academyFundamentals`. \n\n\nIn the following image, the application with the root package `academyfundamentals` is selected:\n\n<img src=\"../src/doc/img/lab2/app-dropdown.png\" alt=\"The dropdown menu with the academyfundamentals application selected.\" width=\"700px\" style=\"padding: inherit; margin:auto; display:block;\"/> ","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Introduction","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"In this lab, you add the final touches to your data model by taking a deeper dive into modifying fields and writing expressions to create calculated fields. \n\nThe following ERD shows the modifications you make to the data model:\n\n<img src=\"../src/doc/img/lab3/erd-highlighted.png\" alt=\"ERD highlighting the changes made in this lab.\" width=\"800px\" style=\"padding: inherit; margin:auto; display:block;\">","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Section 1: Field configurations","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"The C3 AI Type System offers a few ways to customize field behavior. The syntax for adding these configurations is straightforward.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 1.1 Required fields","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"To make a field required, add an exclamation mark `!` before the field data type. This applies to both primitive and non-primitive fields. The following code snippet makes the field `User.email` required.\n\n```javascript\nentity type User {\n    \n    email: !string\n}\n```","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n<h4>Activity 1.1</h4>\n\nUpdate the following fields to make them required:\n<ul>\n    <li><code>Store.address</code></li>\n    <li><code>City.name</code></li>\n    <li><code>Sale.date</code></li>\n</ul>\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After you complete the activity, run the following cells to make sure your code is correct. **These cells should fail.**","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Store.make({id: 'lab3s1'}).create()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["\u001b[31m---------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m","Write failed: Required field Store.address not set."]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402517231,"endTime":1779402517338},"executionOrder":1,"success":false}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"City.make({id: 'BOS'}).create()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["\u001b[31m---------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m","Write failed: Required field City.name not set."]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402518264,"endTime":1779402518340},"executionOrder":2,"success":false}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 1.2 `enum` fields\n\nEnumerated fields, or `enum` fields, are fields that only take a set of possible values for that field. If you need to limit the values for a field or need to work with constants, consider using `enum` fields.\n\nEnum fields can be created in two ways. The first method is to add the configuration directly in the Type. After the field data type, use the `enum` keyword and include the possible values in a list. \n\nThe following code snippet contains an example of this syntax:\n\n```javascript\nentity type Bottle {\n\n    /** \n     * The volume of the plastic bottle, in milliliters.\n     */\n    volume: int enum(500, 1000)\n}\n\n```\n\nYou may also encounter `enum` Types, which is another way to declare the constants in a field. This approach is more reusable than defining an enumerated list in fields, since you can use an enum Type across multiple Type definitions.\n\nAn enum Type is implemented like any other Type, but with the `enum` keyword in the Type declaration. The following code snippet converts the enum values from the previous example into the enum Type, `BottleVolumes`:\n\n```javascript\nenum type BottleVolumes {\n    \n    /**\n     * A constant representing 500ml.\n     */\n    HALF = 500 // These values are optional.\n\n    /**\n     * A constant for a bottle that holds 1000ml of liquid.\n     */\n    LITER = 1000\n}\n\n```\n\nIn the example, `HALF` and `LITER` are the constants. Constants should be defined using UPPER_SNAKE_CASE. Assigning values to the constants is optional. They just need to share the same value type. The values for `HALF` and `LITER` are both integers.\n\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\">\nIt is best practice to put each constant on a separate line with a documentation comment when you define <code>enum</code> Types.\n\nWe recommend using enum Types to declare enumerated fields because they are reusable and the constants can be documented.\n</div>\n\nThe syntax to use this enum Type in the field definition is similar to using the list. The enum Type is specified in place of the parenthesized list.\n\n```javascript\nentity type Bottle mixes Plastic {\n\n    volume: int enum(500, 1000)\n\n    volumeFromBV: int enum BottleVolumes\n}\n\n```","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n<h4>Activity 1.2</h4>\n\nUpdate the <code>Sale</code> Type in your application with the following requirements:\n<ul>\n    <li>Make <code>Sale.paymentMethod</code> an <code>enum</code> field. It should restrict the field to the following strings:</li>\n    <ul>\n        <li>Credit Card</li>\n        <li>Debit Card</li>\n        <li>Cash</li>\n        <li>Mobile Pay</li>\n    </ul>\n    <li>In addition, make <code>Sale.paymentMethod</code> required.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Run the following cell to make sure your code is correct. **The cell should fail.**","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"// This should fail.\nSale.make({id:'testSale', date: '2024-01-15T14:30:00Z', paymentMethod: 'not_right'}).merge()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["\u001b[31m---------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m","Write failed: Enum field 'Sale.paymentMethod' value does not match, should be one of: [Credit Card, Debit Card, Cash, Mobile Payment]. Instead it was: 'not_right'"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402521609,"endTime":1779402521692},"executionOrder":3,"success":false}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\" style=\"background-color:white; color:#106064;\">\n<h4>Bonus Activity 1.2</h4>\n\nReplace the enum field with an enum Type. Create the <code>PaymentMethod</code> Type, which enumerates the possible payment methods supported across all stores. Your implementation needs both the field names, in UPPERCASE_SNAKE_CASE, and the values.\n\n**Note:** You need both constants and values since some of the field values, like \"Credit Card,\" have spaces.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Run the following cells to make sure your code is correct. \n\n**Case 1: Test non-enumerated value**","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Sale.make({'id':'testSale', date: '2024-01-15T14:30:00Z', paymentMethod: 'not_right'}).merge()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["\u001b[31m---------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m","Write failed: Enum field 'Sale.paymentMethod' value does not match, should be one of: [Credit Card, Debit Card, Cash, Mobile Payment]. Instead it was: 'not_right'"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402525644,"endTime":1779402525713},"executionOrder":4,"success":false}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"**Expected result**\n\nThe cell should fail.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"**Case 2: Use enumerated value**","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"// This should succeed.\nSale.make({'id':'testSale', date: '2024-01-15T14:30:00Z', paymentMethod: PaymentMethod.CASH}).merge()\n// Remove the record.\nSale.forId('testSale').remove()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["true"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402527698,"endTime":1779402527904},"executionOrder":5,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"**Expected result**\n\nThe `PaymentMethod` enum Type is defined, with the `CASH` constant defined. The record is created, and then removed (output is `true`).","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Section 2: Calculated fields","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"A calculated field (or calc field) is another type of a non-primitive field. In comparison to the fields created so far in the course, calculated fields derive their values from an expression defined on the field. Remember dot notation? Dot notation is extremely helpful in writing expressions for calc fields.\n\nThere are two types of calc fields:\n- **Read calculated** fields are evaluated in memory, and not persisted. Declare a read calc field using the `calc` keyword in your field. \n- **Stored calculated** fields persist the computed value in the expression. Define stored calc fields using the keywords `stored calc`.\n\nValid expressions are composed of:\n- Logical and mathematical JavaScript operators.\n- Expression engine functions, excluding timeseries functions.\n- Valid paths and fields from the Type the expression is defined on (using dot notation).\n\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\nYou cannot filter or sort on a read calc field because it is computed at runtime.\n</div>\n\nThe following code snippet contains an example of a read calc field, `unitPriceCAD`, on the `Product` Type. The `calc` keyword follows the field value type, then the expression comes after the keyword.\n\n```javascript\nentity type Product {\n\n    /**\n     * Price for a single unit, in USD.\n     */\n    unitPrice: double\n\n    /**\n     * Example calc field of converting the unit price from USD to CAD.\n     */\n    unitPriceCAD: double calc unitPrice * 1.37\n\n}\n```","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n<h4>Activity 2.1</h4>\n\nUpdate <code>LineItem.price</code> to a <b>stored calc</b> field. The expression should multiply the <code>quantity</code> of product in the <code>LineItem</code> with the product's <code>unitPrice</code>.\n\n<b>Hint:</b> Use dot notation to access <code>unitPrice</code>. You can access this field using the <code>product</code> field on <code>LineItem</code>.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"When changes are made to a stored calc field, the values may not automatically recompute and populate. If you make changes to a stored calc field and need to update it, you must refresh the calc fields on the Type.\n\nThe following code snippet refreshes the `LineItem.price`, which should be a stored calc field after completing the activity.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"LineItem.refreshCalcFields({calcFieldsToRefresh: ['price']})","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"c3/notebook","value":["{","\t\"kind\": \"JSON\",","\t\"output\": {","\t\t\"data\": {","\t\t\t\"typeIdent\": \"BATCHJ:REFRESH:REFRCALC\",","\t\t\t\"id\": \"7767e352-6cfb-41b3-a170-9a2b1d568ed0\",","\t\t\t\"meta\": {","\t\t\t\t\"created\": \"2026-05-21T22:34:35Z\",","\t\t\t\t\"updated\": \"2026-05-21T22:34:35Z\",","\t\t\t\t\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-21T22:34:35Z\"","\t\t\t},","\t\t\t\"version\": 1","\t\t},","\t\t\"isGriddable\": false,","\t\t\"isChartable\": false,","\t\t\"chartMeta\": null","\t},","\t\"settings\": {","\t\t\"privateFields\": false,","\t\t\"maxHeight\": 540,","\t\t\"gridRows\": 100,","\t\t\"theme\": \"Default Dark Modern\"","\t}","}"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402874911,"endTime":1779402879104},"executionOrder":8,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After you complete the activity, run the following cell to make sure your code is correct.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Math.abs(LineItem.forId('line_003').price - 49.98) < 0.0001","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["true"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779402883655,"endTime":1779402883729},"executionOrder":9,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n<h4>Activity 2.2</h4>\n\nCreate a new field <code>taxRate</code> on <code>Sale</code>. The expression should be a dot notation expression accessing <code>salesTaxRate</code> on <code>City</code>. \n\nThis new field should also convert the existing value from a percentage to a fractional value. In other words, divide the value from <code>City.salesTaxRate</code> by 100.\n\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After you complete the activity, run the following cells to make sure your code is correct.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Math.abs(Sale.fetch({include: '[id, taxRate]'}).objs.last().taxRate - 0.0775) < 0.0001","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["true"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779403373921,"endTime":1779403374140},"executionOrder":7,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\" style=\"background-color:white; color:#106064;\">\n<h4>Bonus Activity 2.2</h4>\n\n<b>Note:</b> We recommend completing Activity 2.2 before attempting this bonus activity.\n\nIf you inspect the total price for a <code>Sale</code> and its corresponding itemization, you might notice that total price is simply a sum of the prices. This is a mistake, since a sales tax should be charged in the cities that have a sales tax! Luckily, you can update this field to a stored calc field. \n\nChange the <code>Sale.totalPrice</code> to a stored calc field. The expression should apply the sales tax rate of the city the store is in. If you completed Activity 2.2, you can use <code>Sale.taxRate</code> in your expression.\n\nThe final price should be rounded to two decimal places.\n\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-warning\"\">\n<b>Note:</b> If you make changes to the stored calc field, you must refresh it.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Sale.refreshCalcFields({calcFieldsToRefresh: ['totalPrice']})","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"c3/notebook","value":["{","\t\"kind\": \"JSON\",","\t\"output\": {","\t\t\"data\": {","\t\t\t\"typeIdent\": \"BATCHJ:REFRESH:REFRCALC\",","\t\t\t\"id\": \"3ce1a65e-b8b5-41ec-a5b8-be3dc5b4d842\",","\t\t\t\"meta\": {","\t\t\t\t\"created\": \"2026-05-21T22:47:34Z\",","\t\t\t\t\"updated\": \"2026-05-21T22:47:34Z\",","\t\t\t\t\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-21T22:47:34Z\"","\t\t\t},","\t\t\t\"version\": 1","\t\t},","\t\t\"isGriddable\": false,","\t\t\"isChartable\": false,","\t\t\"chartMeta\": null","\t},","\t\"settings\": {","\t\t\"privateFields\": false,","\t\t\"maxHeight\": 540,","\t\t\"gridRows\": 100,","\t\t\"theme\": \"Default Dark Modern\"","\t}","}"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779403654262,"endTime":1779403654452},"executionOrder":16,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After you complete the activity, run the following cells to make sure your code is correct.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Math.abs(Sale.fetch({include: '[id, totalPrice]'}).objs.first().totalPrice - 173.78) < 0.00001","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["true"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779403655835,"endTime":1779403655928},"executionOrder":17,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Summary","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"In this lab, you learned how to configure fields and use calculated fields to derive field values from other fields and Types. ","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### Field configurations","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"You made field values required and restricted the possible values in a field using `enum` fields. \n\nThe following code snippet defines the general syntax for the field configurations covered in this lab:\n\n```javascript\ntype ExampleType {\n\n    /** \n     * This field value is required.\n     */\n    aRequiredField: !int\n\n    /**\n     * The values in this field are restricted to the values\n     * 'C3', 'AI', and 'Academy'.\n     */\n    anEnumField: string enum('C3', 'AI', 'Academy')\n\n    /**\n     * The values for this enum field are constrained by the \n     * constants in `SomeEnumType`.\n     */\n    anotherEnumField: string enum SomeEnumType\n}\n```\n\nYou also learned how to create an enum Type, which uses the `enum` keyword in the Type declaration. The following example of `SomeEnumType` illustrates the enum Type syntax:\n\n```javascript\nenum type SomeEnumType {\n    \n    /**\n     * The first constant.\n     */\n    CONSTANT_1 = 'Constant 1' // These values are optional.\n\n    /**\n     * The Nth constant.\n     */\n    CONSTANT_N = 'Constant N'\n}\n```\n \nRemember the enum Type best practices:\n\n- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for the constants.\n- Each constant should be on its own line.\n- Include docstrings for each constant.\n\n","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### Calculated fields","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"\n\nYou also created calculated fields, which enable you to use other fields on Types and apply logic using expressions to create new values. Stored calculated fields are great to use when you have a field that is frequently used to search or sort that requires logic to be evaluated. \n\nThe following table compares the differences between read and stored calculated fields:\n\n| Read calculated fields           | Stored calculated fields                |\n|----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|\n| Defined with the `calc` keyword  | Defined using the `stored calc` keyword |\n| Evaluated at runtime             | Values are persisted              |\n| Cannot be sorted or filtered     | Can be sorted and filtered        |\n|                                  | May need to be manually refreshed |\n\nYou also learned how to manually refresh stored calc fields. The following code snippet contains the generic syntax for calling `Persistable#refreshCalcFields`:\n\n```javascript\n<MyPersistableType>.refreshCalcFields({calcFieldsToRefresh: ['<FieldOnMyPersistableType>']})\n```","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"-----","output":[],"executionSummary":{}}],"metadata":{"id":"9a58d374-5a4c-4028-a7b3-15d9b70b96a3","appName":"academyfundamentals","serializerVersion":"1","runtime":"js-rhino"}}